{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538137"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:25:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:25:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16143"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16143"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.26,0.02,0.01,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8834"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111268"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8834"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16143"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93400"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4631"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"5787"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21067"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43613"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111268"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of his chronic pain management. He sustained significant injuries in a farming accident two years ago and has been taking long-acting oxycodone since then. He has no other significant medical history. His only other regular medication is paracetamol and short-acting oxycodone as required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe reports gradually increasing use of breakthrough short-acting oxycodone over the past three months despite no change in his activity levels or new injuries. He is concerned that his usual medications are becoming less effective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no new findings on examination of his previous injury sites.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely benefit of rotating to a different opioid?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced risk of addiction","Prevention of future tolerance","Complete reversal of tolerance","Elimination of side effects","Improved analgesia at lower equivalent doses"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of opioid tolerance, characterised by decreasing analgesic effect despite stable dosing. Opioid rotation (switching from one opioid to another) is a well-established strategy for managing opioid tolerance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImproved analgesia at lower equivalent doses\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely benefit of opioid rotation. This occurs because cross-tolerance between different opioids is incomplete, meaning that switching to a new opioid can provide better pain relief at a lower equivalent dose. This phenomenon is due to different opioids having varying receptor binding profiles and metabolic pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete reversal of tolerance\u003C/strong\u003E is not achievable through opioid rotation alone. While the new opioid may be more effective initially, tolerance can still develop over time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElimination of side effects\u003C/strong\u003E is an unrealistic expectation. While some side effects may improve with opioid rotation, common opioid-related side effects like constipation and sedation often persist to some degree.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced risk of addiction\u003C/strong\u003E is not a benefit of opioid rotation. The risk of developing opioid use disorder is related to multiple factors and is not significantly altered by changing between different opioids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevention of future tolerance\u003C/strong\u003E is not possible through opioid rotation. Tolerance is a physiological adaptation that can occur with any opioid over time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen implementing opioid rotation, it is important to use appropriate conversion tables and reduce the calculated equivalent dose to account for incomplete cross-tolerance. Close monitoring is required during the transition period.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Opioid rotation can improve analgesia and reduce side effects in patients with opioid tolerance.","Cross-tolerance between different opioids is incomplete, allowing for improved efficacy with opioid rotation.","When rotating opioids, the equivalent dose should be reduced by 25-50% to account for incomplete cross-tolerance."],"references":["De Iaco F, Mannaioni G, Serra S, Finco G, Sartori S, Gandolfo E, Sansone P, Marinangeli F. Equianalgesia, opioid switch and opioid association in different clinical settings: a narrative review. Eur Rev Med Pharmacol Sci. 2022 Mar;26(6):2000-2017. doi: 10.26355/eurrev_202203_28349. PMID: 35363351. Available online at ; https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35363351/","Smith HS, Peppin JF. Toward a systematic approach to opioid rotation. Journal of pain research. 2014 Oct 17:589-608. Available online at ; https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.2147/JPR.S55782"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93400"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16143"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93400"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-12T00:21:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-12T00:21:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8834"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111268"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4631"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Chronic pain","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-10T15:27:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-10T15:27:08+10:30"},"rela